title: Yellen and Powell warn that the Delta variant is slowing the recovery.
content: The Treasury secretary and the Federal Reserve chair prepared remarks ahead of their testimony today to the Senate Banking Committee.

title: Four Jagged Puzzle Pieces and a Few Weeks for Democrats to Assemble Them
content: The party must keep the government funded, stave off a default, push a $1 trillion infrastructure bill to President Biden and secure the votes for a defining climate change and social policy bill.

title: Pelosi Plans Infrastructure Vote as Safety Net Bill Remains Mired in Rifts
content: The move amounts to a gamble that liberals who have balked at allowing the infrastructure bill to move on its own will support it in a vote on Thursday.

title: American Siblings Barred From Leaving China for 3 Years Return to U.S.
content: Their release coincided with an agreement on Friday that cleared the way for a senior executive of Huawei Technologies, the Chinese telecommunications giant, to return to China.

title: Republicans Block Government Funding, Refusing to Lift Debt Limit
content: Senate Republicans opposed legislation to avert a government shutdown and prevent a debt default at a critical moment for Democrats’ domestic agenda.

title: Texas Republicans propose a new congressional map that aims to protect the party’s incumbents.
content: Rather than trying to make significant gains in the state, where Democrats have been increasingly ascendant in recent years, Republicans appear to be trying to bolster their existing congressional delegation.

title: Biden Administration Moves to Protect Undocumented Young Adults
content: A proposed rule could save the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals program, which a federal judge in Texas found unlawful in July.

title: A top F.D.A. official moved on Monday to take over the agency’s vaccines office.
content: Two leaders of the office had publicly questioned whether the general population needed coronavirus booster shots and recently announced plans to retire.

title: As Sinema resists the budget bill, she is set to raise money from business groups that oppose it.
content: Five groups invited association members to an undisclosed location on Tuesday afternoon to write checks for between $1,000 and $5,800, payable to Sinema for Arizona.

title: Intelligence Agencies Pushed to Use More Commercial Satellites
content: Congress wants the government to turn to the private sector to augment the capabilities of highly classified spy satellites.

title: Biden receives a Pfizer-BioNTech booster and urges more Americans to get a first shot.
content: The move comes only days after federal regulators moved to allow millions of Americans to get Pfizer booster shots.

title: ‘I was wrong’: Liz Cheney announces support for same-sex marriage, reversing a longstanding position.
content: Representative Liz Cheney came out against same-sex marriage in 2013. Her sister, who is gay, wrote online at the time that the decision put her “on the wrong side of history.”

title: Explaining the U.S. Debt Limit and Why It Became a Bargaining Tool
content: Political polarization turned a tool for fiscal responsibility into a recipe for economic calamity.

title: The Secret War Over Pentagon Aid in Fighting Wildfires
content: The military’s satellites excel at spotting new blazes, but for decades they have been mostly off limits to civilian firefighters.

title: No Veggies, No Buns, Few Forks: Schools Scramble to Feed Students Amid Shortages
content: Schools across the country are offering less healthy lunch options as they struggle with dwindling supplies, delayed shipments and fewer cafeteria workers.

title: How an Anti-Trump Plotter in 2016 Became His Champion Against Liz Cheney
content: Harriet Hageman, a Wyoming Republican, is the former president’s choice to take on his leading G.O.P. critic. But five years ago, she tried to overturn his victory in the party’s primary race.

title: Democrats’ spending fight carries high stakes for their candidates in coming elections.

title: Fed Officials Under Fire for 2020 Securities Trading Will Resign
content: Robert S. Kaplan will exit his role as head of the Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas next month. Eric S. Rosengren, the head of the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston, is also retiring earlier than planned.

title: India Walton Beat the Buffalo Mayor in a Primary. He Won’t Give Up.
content: India Walton, the democratic socialist who won the Democratic primary for Buffalo mayor, still faces a challenge from Mayor Byron Brown, who is running a write-in campaign against her.

title: Why Scores of Female Athletes Are Speaking Out on Abortion Rights
content: With a Supreme Court ruling in the balance, an Olympic medalist joined a group of more than 500 athletes supporting reproductive rights.

title: Pelosi Announces Vote on $1 Trillion Bipartisan Infrastructure Bill
content: Speaker Nancy Pelosi of California said that the House would take up the $1 trillion bill on Thursday, hours before government funding is scheduled to lapse.

title: America’s Need to Pay Its Bills Has Spawned a Political Game
content: Republicans and Democrats have long sparred over raising the debt ceiling. But this time, the odds are growing that the U.S. could default.
